<hl>
<seg id=1> Russian Premier Discusses State of Russian Economy </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua Press Agency, Moscow, January 8, Telegram.  Russian Premier Chernomelzin stated at a government meeting on the 8th that the main results achieved by Russia in 1997 were the creation of basic premises for economic growth. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> According to a report by the Russian Communications Agency, Tass, Chernomelzin said, relative to 1996, the Russian domestic product had grown by 1.2 percent, industrial production had grown by 3.2 percent, total retail product growth had been 3.9 percent, the annual inflation rate had been 11 percent, or half that of 1996, and resident income had grown by 2.5 percent. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Chernomelzin also indicated that there had been many domestic problems during the past year, such as poor tax revenues, investment plans that had not been completed, a reduction in the foreign trade surplus, ineffectiveness of financial policies adopted by the government, and so forth. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> When speaking of this year's work, Chernomelzin said that new structural reform and economic growth plans were being drafted and prepared for presentation for discussion at an expanded government meeting to be held on February 26. </seg>
<seg id=6> Based on this plan, the Russian gross domestic product would increase by 2 percent next year and the inflation rate would be decreased to between 5 and 8 percent. </seg>
</p>
